I’m not sure if it was part of their mental illness, but they didn’t want to adapt to change.
With California’s homeless population nearing 130,000, an estimated 43,000 of them may be suffering from serious mental illness.
At Carmen Palarca’s board-and-care, residents now face the possibility of being relocated to Central Valley communities they’ve never visited.
She thinks Progress Foundation, which offers residential treatment options in San Francisco, Napa and Sonoma, is one model to consider.
But Concepción laments that she couldn’t keep it open for residents with mental illness.